Introduction

Since the end of 2019, covid-19 has swept the world. After Two years ,although the virus doesn’t disappear, many people’s mentality has changed from the original nervousness and fear to calmness, and the surrounding tension no longer exists. Some people even regard the virus as a non-threatening one, and do not wear masks in public and are unwilling to get vaccinated. We get the data from the New York times and the main problem we want to solve is 1) whether the current situation of the epidemic is improving or still being severe; 2) What is the realtionship between situation of the epidemic and geographic location; 3) whether the wearing of masks is conducive to the alleviation of the epidemic.

Data Preparation

No_mask desicion

For mask table, we mutate a new column called no_wearing which is an logic factor. If the sum of the probability of never wearing mask, rarely wearing mask and sometimes wearing mask people is larger than 0.5, we set the no_wearing as TRUE which means that there is not enough people wearing masks in that county and there are 194 counties are noted as “TRUE”.

new_mask<-mutate(
  df_mask,
  no_wearing =  (NEVER+RARELY+SOMETIMES > 0.5),
  no_wearing_rate = NEVER+RARELY+SOMETIMES
)
head(new_mask)
## # A tibble: 6 × 8

Combine mask dataset result and the df_county dataset

When we check the data type of the fips in the df_counties and the COUNTYFP in the new_mask dataset, we find that their type are difference and the contents are different . Therefore, we first change the fips in the df_counties into integer type to delete the “0”in the front.

df_counties$fips <- as.integer(df_counties$fips)
head(df_counties)
## # A tibble: 6 × 6
##   date       county    state       fips cases deaths

## 5 2020-01-24 Snohomish Washington 53061     1      0
## 6 2020-01-25 Orange    California  6059     1      0

And we need to add the no_wearing parameter which shows the condition of wearing masks into the df_counties. We choose the inner -join to join the two data set elements and change the fip and COUNTYFP into factor as the key in the progress. The main reason why we choose the inner-join is that we hope there is no NA contant in the new data set.

# get the no_wearing out from the dataset
part_mask <- new_mask[,c(1,7,8)]
#change the type of the COUNTYFP into factor
part_mask$COUNTYFP<-as.factor(part_mask$COUNTYFP)
#change the type of the fips into factor
df_counties_all<-df_counties
df_counties_all$fips<-as.factor(df_counties_all$fips)
#inner join 
df_counties_all<-inner_join(df_counties_all,part_mask,by = c("fips"="COUNTYFP") )
head(df_counties_all)

Mask wearing rate in state level

Because we only get the average cases happened per 100k people and the average death happened per 100k people data in each state instead of the , to make our follow analysis more accurate, we need to calculate the average no wearing mask rate in state level.

average_mask_wearing<- df_counties_all%>%
     group_by(state)%>%
     summarise(avg_mask = mean(no_wearing_rate))

What’s more, we want to study the relationship between geographic location and epidemic situation, so we need to calculate the number of cases and death in each area.

df_region<- df_state%>%
     group_by(date,region_name)%>%
     summarise(cases= sum(cases_avg),
               cases_avg_per_100k = mean(cases_avg_per_100k),
               deaths  = sum(deaths),
               deaths_avg_per_100k = mean(deaths_avg_per_100k),
               mask_wearing = mean(avg_mask)
               )
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'date'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Regarding the third question, we need to study whether the wearing of masks can help control the spread of the epidemic and because the survey on mask wearing was conducted in July 2020, our data focuses on July 2020. We count the mean of confirmed patients in July.

average_mask_wearing_state<- df_state%>%
     group_by(state) %>%
     filter(date >"2020-6-30")  %>%
     filter(date <"2020-8-1") %>%
     summarise(mask_wearing = 1-mean(avg_mask),
               cases_avg_per_100k = mean(cases_avg_per_100k)
               )
head(average_mask_wearing_state)

Data Visualization and Descriptive Analysis

Current situation of the epidemic in nation level

To get the current situation of the covid-19 in the US, we first plot the line chart of the cumulative number of confirmed cases and the deaths happened in the US from 2020-1 to 2021-12.

df_nation %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = date, y = cases)) +
  geom_line()+
  labs(title = "Number of Confirmed Cases in the US",
         subtitle = "cumulative number",
  )

df_nation %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = date, y = deaths)) +
  geom_line()+
   labs(title = "Death Happens in the US because of the covied-19",
         subtitle = "cumulative number",
  )

By observing the above two graphs, we can clearly find that the number of deaths and the overall trend of the number of infections are the same and positively correlated. From the discovery of the first confirmed patient in January 2020 to more than 50 million confirmed cases and more than 80,000 deaths across the country, there are two major turning points, namely November 2020 and September 2021. These two rapidly increasing time points corresponded to the emergence and outbreak of mutant strains alpha and delta. From this we can clearly realize that the emergence of mutant strains poses a great threat to the control of the epidemic in the United States. We can infer that the newly reported new variance virus Omicron, a new variant of covid-19 with more infectiousness, will pose a greater threat to the epidemic situation in the United States.

Covid-19 situation and Geographic location

We divided the data into four regions based on geographic location, namely Midwest, Northeast, South, West. Because each region contains different number of states and populations, we study the average number of confirmed cases and deaths per 100k people. The time range is from January 2020 to December 2021.

df_region %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = date, y = deaths_avg_per_100k, color = region_name))+
  geom_line()+
  labs(title = "Number of Deaths in each Region",
         subtitle = "average cases happens per 100k",
  )

From the figure, we can see that the Northeast region was initially most affected by the covid-19 virus, and then the Midwest region was affected by the alpha strain in October 2020 much higher than other regions, but the control measures were more effective and the epidemic situation was very fast. Under control. The recent gama strain seems to have a greater impact on the South region. Generally speaking, the control of the epidemic in the western region is relatively stable compared to the other three regions. For the past three months, the situation in Northeast has been good.

In addition, the results obtained by analyzing the two figures above are roughly the same as the results of the overall analysis of the US epidemic. The number of confirmed cases and the number of deaths are positively correlated as a whole. In terms of the daily number of confirmed diagnoses and deaths in the past three months, November to December has a trend of improvement compared with September and October, but compared with the situation in April and May, it is still not optimistic.

Covid-19 situation and mask_wearing

We draw a scatter plot of the mask wearing rate and the number of confirmed cases.

average_mask_wearing_state %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = mask_wearing, y = cases_avg_per_100k))+
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Mask_wearing VS Case happen",
         subtitle = "average cases happens per 100k",
  )

Reading the above picture, it is surprising that when the mask wearing rate is between 0.7 and 0.8, the number of confirmed cases is higher than in other cases. When the mask wearing rate is above 0.8, the number of confirmed cases reaches the lowest. It can be seen that when the proportion of wearing masks is large enough, it is beneficial to the control of the epidemic. It can also be seen that the situation of the epidemic is not only related to the rate of wearing masks, but may have other influencing factors.

Conclution

Based on the above research, it is not difficult for us to find that the situation of the epidemic situation in the United States is closely related to the outbreak of the mutant virus and that the current situation of the epidemic situation is not optimistic. You should still treat the epidemic with caution and not take it lightly. The overall situation of the epidemic is not closely related to the geographical location, and may be related to the local epidemic prevention policy. The government should encourage people to wear masks. When the mask wearing rate reaches 80% or more, the epidemic situation will improve.
